# Useful reading

## Sample size & Most Frequent Words
* Eder, M. “Does Size Matter? Authorship Attribution, Small Samples, Big Problem.” Literary and Linguistic Computing, vol. 30, no. 2, June 2015, pp. 167–82.  
* Eder, M. "Short samples in authorship attribution: a new approach." DH 2017 Book of Abstracts, [link](https://dh2017.adho.org/abstracts/341/341.pdf)
* Rybicki, J., and Eder, M. “Deeper Delta across Genres and Languages: Do We Really Need the Most Frequent Words?” Literary and Linguistic Computing, vol. 26, no. 3, Sept. 2011, pp. 315–21.  

## Networks
* Eder, M. “Visualization in Stylometry: Cluster Analysis Using Networks.” Digital Scholarship in the Humanities, vol. 32, no. 1, Apr. 2017, pp. 50–64.  

## The method behind oppose()
* Craig, H., and Kinney, A. F. “Methods.” in Shakespeare, Computers, and the Mystery of Authorship, Cambridge University Press, 2009, p. 15-40.
* Burrows, J. “All the Way Through: Testing for Authorship in Different Frequency Strata.” Literary and Linguistic Computing, vol. 22, no. 1, Apr. 2007, pp. 27–47.
* Hoover, D. L. “Teasing Out Authorship and Style with T-Tests and Zeta”. DH2010 Book of Abstracts.

## Culling
* Hoover, D.L. [Testing Burrows's Delta](https://academic.oup.com/dsh/article-abstract/19/4/453/943644?redirectedFrom=fulltext)
* Hoover, D.L. [Delta Prime?](https://academic.oup.com/dsh/article-abstract/19/4/477/943645?redirectedFrom=fulltext)

## SVM
* Learn more about SVM as implemented in stylo [doc](https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/e1071/e1071.pdf)
* Learn more about SVM via video [Click.](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v7H5ks5iDEQ)

## Books
[James Pennebaker - The Secret Life of Pronouns](http://www.secretlifeofpronouns.com/) - book on how gender (and many other factors) determines our use of pronouns.

## Stylometry Bibliography
[Large repository, tagged for specific issues](https://www.zotero.org/groups/643516/stylometry_bibliography)
